      "I found 10 highly relevant results from February 2026 about AI agent memory and persistent memory in coding agents. Here's a summary of the key findings:\n\n## Key Search Results\n\n### 1. **OpenClaw (Clawdbot) Persistent Memory System** (Jan 30, 2026)\n- **Memory vs Context**: Clear distinction that Memory ≠ Context\n- **Memory = MEMORY.md + memory/*.md + Session Transcripts**\n- **Characteristics**: Persistent (across restarts/days/months) and Unbounded (infinite growth)\n- Files stored together in agent workspace for full transparency and editability\n\n### 2. **Microsoft Foundry Agent Service** (Feb 18, 2026)\n- **Managed long-term memory store** (Public Preview)\n- Automatic extraction, consolidation, and retrieval across agent interactions\n- Native integration with agent runtime\n- References `Azure.AI.Agents.Persistent` at version 1.2.0-beta.8\n\n### 3. **2026 AI Agent Memory Trends** (Feb 2026)\nMultiple sources highlight that 2026 is the \"Year of Long-Horizon Agents\" with major memory breakthroughs:\n\n- **Three-layer memory architecture** for fully automated AI agents\n- **Short-term memory**: Context window expansion from thousands to tens of thousands of tokens\n- **Long-term memory**: Memory Bear systems with human-like architecture integrating multimodal perception\n- **Memory as reflection**: Agents can review and learn from error traces to update their knowledge\n\n### 4. **Coding Agent Memory Evolution** (Feb 6-9, 2026)\n- Shift from pure Embedding to **AST (Abstract Syntax Tree)**, **Agentic FS Graph**, or **AST Graph** for code retrieval\n- Memory engines ensure agents \"remember\" user preferences and interaction history\n- Enables task continuity without re-explaining requirements each time\n\n### 5. **Microsoft Python + Agents Series** (Feb 24-25, 2026)\n- Dedicated session on \"Adding context and memory to agents\"\n- Covers both **short-term thread-level context** and **long-term persistent memory**\n\n## Key Insights for February 2026:\n- **Persistent memory** is now a production-grade feature, not experimental\n- **Memory transparency** (storing in editable files like Markdown) is a key design pattern\n- **Self-reflection mechanisms** allow agents to learn from their own error traces\n- **Multi-layer memory architectures** combining context windows with persistent storage are standard\n- The industry is moving beyond chat-based AI to **Long-Horizon Agents** that can work autonomously for extended periods"
