      "Based on my web search, here are the key findings about **project memory**, **workspace memory**, and **cross-session memory** for AI agents from February 2026:\n\n## Major Development: OpenClaw Memory System\n\nThe most significant development is **OpenClaw** (formerly Clawdbot/Moltbot), an open-source personal AI agent framework that has achieved massive popularity (161K+ GitHub stars in February 2026). Its memory system implements all three concepts you searched for:\n\n### **Project/Workspace Memory**\n- **Storage Location**: `~/.openclaw/workspace/` directory\n- **Format**: Plain Markdown files (human-readable and editable)\n- **Structure**:\n  - `MEMORY.md` - Long-term persistent facts and preferences\n  - `memory/` - Daily chronological logs (e.g., `memory/2026-02-13.md`)\n  - Other project-specific files like `opinions.md`, `entities/` folder\n- **Plugin Integration**: Official integration with LanceDB as the third-party memory backend\n\n### **Cross-Session Memory Solutions**\n\nSeveral approaches emerged in February 2026:\n\n1. **OpenClaw's Native Solution**:\n   - Daily memory archives (`memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md`)\n   - 24-hour rolling event logs (`RECENT_EVENTS.md`)\n   - Intelligent retrieval of relevant historical records to avoid context overload\n   - Session reads relevant memory at start, writes new memory at end\n\n2. **EvoMap's \"Capsule\" System**:\n   - Provides pre-packaged solutions for \"session amnesia\"\n   - Agents query solution patterns via `POST /a2a/fetch`\n   - Automates implementation of cross-session memory\n\n3. **Code-Relay Protocol**:\n   - Structured protocol enabling self-bootstrapping\n   - Cross-session memory for AI coding agents\n   - Multi-repo global awareness\n\n## Industry Trends\n\n### **\"Agentic Memory\" as 2026's Hot Trend**\n\nFebruary 2026 saw intense competition in the AI memory space:\n\n- **MemBrain 1.0** by Feeling AI achieved SOTA on multiple benchmarks (LoCoMo, LongMemEval, PersonaMem-v2)\n- **300% performance improvement** on Level III evaluations\n- Industry consensus: \"Agents without memory are just advanced autocomplete tools\"\n- **Sequoia Capital** identifies \"persistent identity\" as a core challenge for future agents\n\n### **Key Architecture Patterns**\n\n1. **Three-Tier File Structure**:\n   - Session memory (short-term)\n   - Daily logs (medium-term)\n   - Long-term memory (persistent facts)\n\n2. **Hybrid Retrieval**:\n   - Vector search for semantic relevance\n   - Metadata filtering for temporal constraints\n   - Smart context injection to manage token limits\n\n3. **Integration Points**:\n   - Tools: `memory_search` and `memory_get` for agent access\n   - Database backends: SQLite + vector indexes\n   - File system monitoring for real-time updates\n\n## Key Insight from February 2026\n\nThe industry has reached a consensus that **memory is the critical differentiator** between basic chatbots and truly useful AI agents. The shift from increasing context windows to implementing structured, persistent memory systems represents a fundamental evolution in AI agent architecture."
