      "Based on the search results, here's what I found about **GitHub Agentic Workflows** and its February 2026 release:\n\n## Overview\nGitHub announced that **Agentic Workflows** entered **technical preview** on **February 18, 2026**. This is a major new feature that allows developers to delegate routine repository maintenance and collaboration tasks to AI agents within the GitHub Actions automation platform.\n\n## Key Features\n\n### 🔧 **Capabilities**\n- **Issue triage and label management**\n- **Pull Request review**\n- **Continuous Integration (CI) failure analysis**\n- **Documentation and code quality maintenance**\n- Natural language-based automation definition (reduces need for complex YAML)\n\n### 🔒 **Security Features**\n- **Default read-only permissions** for AI agents\n- **safe-outputs mechanism** required for any write operations (creating issues, commenting, submitting PRs, adding labels)\n- Prevents malicious poisoning of automated content\n- Sandboxed execution environment\n- Can integrate with Agent Workflow Firewall and MCP Gateway\n\n### 📦 **Technical Details**\n- **Open source** with MIT license\n- Repository: `github/gh-aw`\n- Languages: Go (74.6%), JavaScript (23.8%), Shell (1.4%)\n- Current version: v0.44.0 (as of February 2026)\n- Runs on GitHub Actions platform\n- Developers can define workflows using natural language Markdown\n\n### 📈 **Impact**\nAccording to reports, this feature can reduce 3 hours of routine tasks and increase efficiency by up to 10x for developers. It marks GitHub's transition from a code storage tool to an intelligent collaboration platform.\n\n### ⚠️ **Important Note**\nGitHub emphasizes that Agentic Workflows are **not replacements** for build, test, or release pipelines, and their use cases largely do not overlap with deterministic CI/CD workflows.\n\nThe feature is currently in technical preview, with GitHub collaborating with partners and the community to improve it before a full general release."
